member.summary: A case series (also known as a clinical series) is a medical research study that tracks patients with a known exposure given similar treatment or examines their medical records for exposure and outcome. member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.CohortStudy
member.summary: Also known as a panel study. A cohort study is a form of longitudinal study used in medicine and social science. It is one type of study design and should be compared with a cross-sectional study. A cohort is a group of people who share a common characteristic or experience within a defined period (e.g., are born, leave school, lose their job, are exposed to a drug or a vaccine, etc.). The comparison group may be the general population from which the cohort is drawn, or it may be another cohort of persons thought to have had little or no exposure to the substance under investigation, but otherwise similar. Alternatively, subgroups within the cohort may be compared with each other.

member.summary: A day spa.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DDxElement
member.summary: An alternative, closely-related condition typically considered later in the differential diagnosis process along with the signs that are used to distinguish it.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DDxElement.Diagnosis
member.summary: One or more alternative conditions considered in the differential diagnosis process.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DDxElement.DistinguishingSign
member.summary: One of a set of signs and symptoms that can be used to distinguish this diagnosis from others in the differential diagnosis.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DefenceEstablishment

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DeliveryChargeSpecification
member.summary: The price for the delivery of an offer using a particular delivery method.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.PriceSpecification
member.summary: A structured value representing a monetary amount. Typically, only the subclasses of this type are used for markup.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.PriceSpecification.EligibleQuantity
member.summary: The interval and unit of measurement of ordering quantities for which the offer or price specification is valid. This allows e.g. specifying that a certain freight charge is valid only for a certain quantity.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.PriceSpecification.EligibleTransactionVolume
member.summary: The transaction volume, in a monetary unit, for which the offer or price specification is valid, e.g. for indicating a minimal purchasing volume, to express free shipping above a certain order volume, or to limit the acceptance of credit cards to purchases to a certain minimal amount.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.PriceSpecification.MaxPrice
member.summary: The highest price if the price is a range.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.PriceSpecification.MinPrice
member.summary: The lowest price if the price is a range.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.PriceSpecification.Price
member.summary: The offer price of a product, or of a price component when attached to PriceSpecification and its subtypes.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.PriceSpecification.PriceCurrency
member.summary: The currency (in 3-letter ISO 4217 format) of the offer price or a price component, when attached to PriceSpecification and its subtypes.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.PriceSpecification.ValidFrom
member.summary: The beginning of the validity of offer, price specification, or opening hours data.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.PriceSpecification.ValidThrough
member.summary: The end of the validity of offer, price specification, or opening hours data.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.PriceSpecification.ValueAddedTaxIncluded
member.summary: Specifies whether the applicable value-added tax (VAT) is included in the price specification or not.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DeliveryChargeSpecification.AppliesToDeliveryMethod
member.summary: The delivery method(s) to which the delivery charge or payment charge specification applies.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DeliveryChargeSpecification.EligibleRegion
member.summary: The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is valid.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DeliveryMethod
member.summary:
A delivery method is a standardized procedure for transferring the product or service to the destination of fulfilment chosen by the customer. Delivery methods are characterized by the means of transportation used, and by the organization or group that is the contracting party for the sending organization or person.
Commonly used values:
http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeDirectDownload http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeFreight http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeMail http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeOwnFleet http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModePickUp http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DHL http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#FederalExpress http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#UPS

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand
member.summary: A demand entity represents the public, not necessarily binding, not necessarily exclusive, announcement by an organization or person to seek a certain type of goods or services. For describing demand using this type, the very same properties used for Offer apply.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.AcceptedPaymentMethod
member.summary: The payment method(s) accepted by seller for this offer.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.AdvanceBookingRequirement
member.summary: The amount of time that is required between accepting the offer and the actual usage of the resource or service.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.Availability
member.summary: The availability of this item—for example In stock, Out of stock, Pre-order, etc.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.AvailabilityEnds
member.summary: The end of the availability of the product or service included in the offer.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.AvailabilityStarts
member.summary: The beginning of the availability of the product or service included in the offer.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.AvailableAtOrFrom
member.summary: The place(s) from which the offer can be obtained (e.g. store locations).

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.AvailableDeliveryMethod
member.summary: The delivery method(s) available for this offer.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.BusinessFunction
member.summary: The business function (e.g. sell, lease, repair, dispose) of the offer or component of a bundle (TypeAndQuantityNode). The default is http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Sell.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.DeliveryLeadTime
member.summary: The typical delay between the receipt of the order and the goods leaving the warehouse.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.EligibleCustomerType
member.summary: The type(s) of customers for which the given offer is valid.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.EligibleDuration
member.summary: The duration for which the given offer is valid.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.EligibleQuantity
member.summary: The interval and unit of measurement of ordering quantities for which the offer or price specification is valid. This allows e.g. specifying that a certain freight charge is valid only for a certain quantity.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.EligibleRegion
member.summary: The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is valid.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.EligibleTransactionVolume
member.summary: The transaction volume, in a monetary unit, for which the offer or price specification is valid, e.g. for indicating a minimal purchasing volume, to express free shipping above a certain order volume, or to limit the acceptance of credit cards to purchases to a certain minimal amount.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.Gtin13
member.summary: The GTIN-13 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This is equivalent to 13-digit ISBN codes and EAN UCC-13. Former 12-digit UPC codes can be converted into a GTIN-13 code by simply adding a preceeding zero.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.Gtin14
member.summary: The GTIN-14 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.Gtin8
member.summary: The GTIN-8 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This code is also known as EAN/UCC-8 or 8-digit EAN.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.IncludesObject
member.summary: This links to a node or nodes indicating the exact quantity of the products included in the offer.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.InventoryLevel
member.summary: The current approximate inventory level for the item or items.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.ItemCondition
member.summary: A predefined value from OfferItemCondition or a textual description of the condition of the product or service, or the products or services included in the offer.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.ItemOffered
member.summary: The item being sold.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.Mpn
member.summary: The Manufacturer Part Number (MPN) of the product, or the product to which the offer refers.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.PriceSpecification
member.summary: One or more detailed price specifications, indicating the unit price and delivery or payment charges.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.Seller
member.summary: The seller.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.SerialNumber
member.summary: The serial number or any alphanumeric identifier of a particular product. When attached to an offer, it is a shortcut for the serial number of the product included in the offer.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.Sku
member.summary: The Stock Keeping Unit (SKU), i.e. a merchant-specific identifier for a product or service, or the product to which the offer refers.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.ValidFrom
member.summary: The beginning of the validity of offer, price specification, or opening hours data.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.ValidThrough
member.summary: The end of the validity of offer, price specification, or opening hours data.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Demand.Warranty
member.summary: The warranty promise(s) included in the offer.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Dentist
member.summary: A dentist.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Dentistry
member.summary: Dentistry.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DepartmentStore
member.summary: A department store.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Dermatologic
member.summary: A specific branch of medical science that pertains to diagnosis and treatment of disorders of skin.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Diagnostic
member.summary: A medical device used for diagnostic purposes.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalDevicePurpose
member.summary: Categories of medical devices, organized by the purpose or intended use of the device.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DiagnosticLab
member.summary: A medical laboratory that offers on-site or off-site diagnostic services.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalOrganization
member.summary: A medical organization, such as a doctor's office or clinic.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DiagnosticLab.AvailableTest
member.summary: A diagnostic test or procedure offered by this lab.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DiagnosticProcedure
member.summary: A medical procedure intended primarly for diagnostic, as opposed to therapeutic, purposes.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Diet
member.summary: A strategy of regulating the intake of food to achieve or maintain a specific health-related goal.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.LifestyleModification
member.summary: A process of care involving exercise, changes to diet, fitness routines, and other lifestyle changes aimed at improving a health condition.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalTherapy
member.summary: Any medical intervention designed to prevent, treat, and cure human diseases and medical conditions, including both curative and palliative therapies. Medical therapies are typically processes of care relying upon pharmacotherapy, behavioral therapy, supportive therapy (with fluid or nutrition for example), or detoxification (e.g. hemodialysis) aimed at improving or preventing a health condition.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalTherapy.AdverseOutcome
member.summary: A possible complication and/or side effect of this therapy. If it is known that an adverse outcome is serious (resulting in death, disability, or permanent damage; requiring hospitalization; or is otherwise life-threatening or requires immediate medical attention), tag it as a seriouseAdverseOutcome instead.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalTherapy.Contraindication
member.summary: A contraindication for this therapy.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalTherapy.DuplicateTherapy
member.summary: A therapy that duplicates or overlaps this one.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalTherapy.Indication
member.summary: A factor that indicates use of this therapy for treatment and/or prevention of a condition, symptom, etc. For therapies such as drugs, indications can include both officially-approved indications as well as off-label uses. These can be distinguished by using the ApprovedIndication subtype of MedicalIndication.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalTherapy.SeriousAdverseOutcome
member.summary: A possible serious complication and/or serious side effect of this therapy. Serious adverse outcomes include those that are life-threatening; result in death, disability, or permanent damage; require hospitalization or prolong existing hospitalization; cause congenital anomalies or birth defects; or jeopardize the patient and may require medical or surgical intervention to prevent one of the outcomes in this definition.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Diet.DietFeatures
member.summary: Nutritional information specific to the dietary plan. May include dietary recommendations on what foods to avoid, what foods to consume, and specific alterations/deviations from the USDA or other regulatory body's approved dietary guidelines.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Diet.Endorsers
member.summary: People or organizations that endorse the plan.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Diet.ExpertConsiderations
member.summary: Medical expert advice related to the plan.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Diet.Overview
member.summary: Descriptive information establishing the overarching theory/philosophy of the plan. May include the rationale for the name, the population where the plan first came to prominence, etc.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Diet.PhysiologicalBenefits
member.summary: Specific physiologic benefits associated to the plan.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Diet.ProprietaryName
member.summary: Proprietary name given to the diet plan, typically by its originator or creator.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Diet.Risks
member.summary: Specific physiologic risks associated to the plan.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DietarySupplement
member.summary: A product taken by mouth that contains a dietary ingredient intended to supplement the diet. Dietary ingredients may include vitamins, minerals, herbs or other botanicals, amino acids, and substances such as enzymes, organ tissues, glandulars and metabolites.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DietarySupplement.ActiveIngredient
member.summary: An active ingredient, typically chemical compounds and/or biologic substances.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DietarySupplement.Background
member.summary: Descriptive information establishing a historical perspective on the supplement. May include the rationale for the name, the population where the supplement first came to prominence, etc.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DietarySupplement.DosageForm
member.summary: A dosage form in which this drug/supplement is available, e.g. 'tablet', 'suspension', 'injection'.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DietarySupplement.IsProprietary
member.summary: True if this item's name is a proprietary/brand name (vs. generic name).

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DietarySupplement.LegalStatus
member.summary: The drug or supplement's legal status, including any controlled substance schedules that apply.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DietarySupplement.Manufacturer
member.summary: The manufacturer of the product.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DietarySupplement.MaximumIntake
member.summary: Recommended intake of this supplement for a given population as defined by a specific recommending authority.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DietarySupplement.MechanismOfAction
member.summary: The specific biochemical interaction through which this drug or supplement produces its pharmacological effect.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DietarySupplement.NonProprietaryName
member.summary: The generic name of this drug or supplement.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DietarySupplement.RecommendedIntake
member.summary: Recommended intake of this supplement for a given population as defined by a specific recommending authority.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DietarySupplement.SafetyConsideration
member.summary: Any potential safety concern associated with the supplement. May include interactions with other drugs and foods, pregnancy, breastfeeding, known adverse reactions, and documented efficacy of the supplement.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DietarySupplement.TargetPopulation
member.summary: Characteristics of the population for which this is intended, or which typically uses it, e.g. 'adults'.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DietNutrition
member.summary: Diet and nutrition.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Discontinued
member.summary: Indicates that the item for sale has been discontinued.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.ItemAvailability
member.summary: A list of possible product availablity options.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Quantity
member.summary: Quantities such as distance, time, mass, weight, etc. Particular instances of say Mass are entities like '3 Kg' or '4 milligrams'.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DoseSchedule
member.summary: A specific dosing schedule for a drug or supplement.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DoseSchedule.DoseUnit
member.summary: The unit of the dose, e.g. 'mg'.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DoseSchedule.DoseValue
member.summary: The value of the dose, e.g. 500.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DoseSchedule.Frequency
member.summary: How often the dose is taken, e.g. 'daily'.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DoseSchedule.TargetPopulation
member.summary: Characteristics of the population for which this is intended, or which typically uses it, e.g. 'adults'.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.DoubleBlindedTrial
member.summary: A trial design in which neither the researcher nor the patient knows the details of the treatment the patient was randomly assigned to.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalTrialDesign
member.summary: Design models for medical trials. Enumerated type.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Drug
member.summary: A chemical or biologic substance, used as a medical therapy, that has a physiological effect on an organism.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Drug.ActiveIngredient
member.summary: An active ingredient, typically chemical compounds and/or biologic substances.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Drug.AdministrationRoute
member.summary: A route by which this drug may be administered, e.g. 'oral'.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Drug.AlcoholWarning
member.summary: Any precaution, guidance, contraindication, etc. related to consumption of alcohol while taking this drug.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Drug.AvailableStrength
member.summary: An available dosage strength for the drug.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Drug.BreastfeedingWarning
member.summary: Any precaution, guidance, contraindication, etc. related to this drug's use by breastfeeding mothers.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Drug.ClincalPharmacology
member.summary: Description of the absorption and elimination of drugs, including their concentration (pharmacokinetics, pK) and biological effects (pharmacodynamics, pD).

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Drug.Cost
member.summary: Cost per unit of the drug, as reported by the source being tagged.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Drug.DosageForm
member.summary: A dosage form in which this drug/supplement is available, e.g. 'tablet', 'suspension', 'injection'.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Drug.DoseSchedule
member.summary: A dosing schedule for the drug for a given population, either observed, recommended, or maximum dose based on the type used.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Drug.DrugClass
member.summary: The class of drug this belongs to (e.g., statins).

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Drug.FoodWarning
member.summary: Any precaution, guidance, contraindication, etc. related to consumption of specific foods while taking this drug.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Drug.InteractingDrug
member.summary: Another drug that is known to interact with this drug in a way that impacts the effect of this drug or causes a risk to the patient. Note: disease interactions are typically captured as contraindications.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Drug.IsAvailableGenerically
member.summary: True if the drug is available in a generic form (regardless of name).

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Drug.IsProprietary
member.summary: True if this item's name is a proprietary/brand name (vs. generic name).

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Drug.LabelDetails
member.summary: Link to the drug's label details.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Drug.LegalStatus
member.summary: The drug or supplement's legal status, including any controlled substance schedules that apply.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Drug.Manufacturer
member.summary: The manufacturer of the product.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Drug.MechanismOfAction
member.summary: The specific biochemical interaction through which this drug or supplement produces its pharmacological effect.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Drug.NonProprietaryName
member.summary: The generic name of this drug or supplement.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Drug.Overdosage
member.summary: Any information related to overdose on a drug, including signs or symptoms, treatments, contact information for emergency response.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Drug.PregnancyCategory
member.summary: Pregnancy category of this drug.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Drug.PregnancyWarning
member.summary: Any precaution, guidance, contraindication, etc. related to this drug's use during pregnancy.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.FDAcategoryA
member.summary: A designation by the US FDA signifying that adequate and well-controlled studies have failed to demonstrate a risk to the fetus in the first trimester of pregnancy (and there is no evidence of risk in later trimesters).

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.FDAcategoryB
member.summary: A designation by the US FDA signifying that animal reproduction studies have failed to demonstrate a risk to the fetus and there are no adequate and well-controlled studies in pregnant women.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.FDAcategoryC
member.summary: A designation by the US FDA signifying that animal reproduction studies have shown an adverse effect on the fetus and there are no adequate and well-controlled studies in humans, but potential benefits may warrant use of the drug in pregnant women despite potential risks.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.FDAcategoryD
member.summary: A designation by the US FDA signifying that there is positive evidence of human fetal risk based on adverse reaction data from investigational or marketing experience or studies in humans, but potential benefits may warrant use of the drug in pregnant women despite potential risks.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.FDAcategoryX
member.summary: A designation by the US FDA signifying that studies in animals or humans have demonstrated fetal abnormalities and/or there is positive evidence of human fetal risk based on adverse reaction data from investigational or marketing experience, and the risks involved in use of the drug in pregnant women clearly outweigh potential benefits.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.FDAnotEvaluated

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.Infectious
member.summary: A specific branch of medical science that pertains to diagnosis and treatment of bacterial, viral, fungal and parasitic infections.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.InfectiousDisease
member.summary: An infectious disease is a clinically evident human disease resulting from the presence of pathogenic microbial agents, like pathogenic viruses, pathogenic bacteria, fungi, protozoa, multicellular parasites, and prions. To be considered an infectious disease, such pathogens are known to be able to cause this disease.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition
member.summary: Any condition of the human body that affects the normal functioning of a person, whether physically or mentally. Includes diseases, injuries, disabilities, disorders, syndromes, etc.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.AssociatedAnatomy
member.summary: The anatomy of the underlying organ system or structures associated with this entity.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.Cause
member.summary: An underlying cause. More specifically, one of the causative agent(s) that are most directly responsible for the pathophysiologic process that eventually results in the occurrence.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.DifferentialDiagnosis
member.summary: One of a set of differential diagnoses for the condition. Specifically, a closely-related or competing diagnosis typically considered later in the cognitive process whereby this medical condition is distinguished from others most likely responsible for a similar collection of signs and symptoms to reach the most parsimonious diagnosis or diagnoses in a patient.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.Epidemiology
member.summary: The characteristics of associated patients, such as age, gender, race etc.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.ExpectedPrognosis
member.summary: The likely outcome in either the short term or long term of the medical condition.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.NaturalProgression
member.summary: The expected progression of the condition if it is not treated and allowed to progress naturally.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.Pathophysiology
member.summary: Changes in the normal mechanical, physical, and biochemical functions that are associated with this activity or condition.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.PossibleComplication
member.summary: A possible unexpected and unfavorable evolution of a medical condition. Complications may include worsening of the signs or symptoms of the disease, extension of the condition to other organ systems, etc.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.PossibleTreatment
member.summary: A possible treatment to address this condition, sign or symptom.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.PrimaryPrevention
member.summary: A preventative therapy used to prevent an initial occurrence of the medical condition, such as vaccination.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.RiskFactor
member.summary: A modifiable or non-modifiable factor that increases the risk of a patient contracting this condition, e.g. age, coexisting condition.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.SecondaryPrevention
member.summary: A preventative therapy used to prevent reoccurrence of the medical condition after an initial episode of the condition.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.SignOrSymptom
member.summary: A sign or symptom of this condition. Signs are objective or physically observable manifestations of the medical condition while symptoms are the subjective experienceof the medical condition.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.Stage
member.summary: The stage of the condition, if applicable.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.Subtype
member.summary: A more specific type of the condition, where applicable, for example 'Type 1 Diabetes', 'Type 2 Diabetes', or 'Gestational Diabetes' for Diabetes.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.TypicalTest
member.summary: A medical test typically performed given this condition.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.InfectiousDisease.InfectiousAgent
member.summary: The actual infectious agent, such as a specific bacterium.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.InfectiousDisease.InfectiousAgentClass
member.summary: The class of infectious agent (bacteria, prion, etc.) that causes the disease.

member.name: P:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.InfectiousDisease.TransmissionMethod
member.summary: How the disease spreads, either as a route or vector, for example 'direct contact', 'Aedes aegypti', etc.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalCause
member.summary: The causative agent(s) that are responsible for the pathophysiologic process that eventually results in a medical condition, symptom or sign. In this schema, unless otherwise specified this is meant to be the proximate cause of the medical condition, symptom or sign. The proximate cause is defined as the causative agent that most directly results in the medical condition, symptom or sign. For example, the HIV virus could be considered a cause of AIDS. Or in a diagnostic context, if a patient fell and sustained a hip fracture and two days later sustained a pulmonary embolism which eventuated in a cardiac arrest, the cause of the cardiac arrest (the proximate cause) would be the pulmonary embolism and not the fall.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalObservationalStudy
member.summary: An observational study is a type of medical study that attempts to infer the possible effect of a treatment through observation of a cohort of subjects over a period of time. In an observational study, the assignment of subjects into treatment groups versus control groups is outside the control of the investigator. This is in contrast with controlled studies, such as the randomized controlled trials represented by MedicalTrial, where each subject is randomly assigned to a treatment group or a control group before the start of the treatment.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.MedicalStudy
member.summary: A medical study is an umbrella type covering all kinds of research studies relating to human medicine or health, including observational studies and interventional trials and registries, randomized, controlled or not. When the specific type of study is known, use one of the extensions of this type, such as MedicalTrial or MedicalObservationalStudy. Also, note that this type should be used to mark up data that describes the study itself; to tag an article that publishes the results of a study, use MedicalScholarlyArticle. Note: use the code property of MedicalEntity to store study IDs, e.g. clinicaltrials.gov ID.

member.name: T:KLGates.Core.Schema.Org.SuperficialAnatomy
member.summary: Anatomical features that can be observed by sight (without dissection), including the form and proportions of the human body as well as surface landmarks that correspond to deeper subcutaneous structures. Superficial anatomy plays an important role in sports medicine, phlebotomy, and other medical specialties as underlying anatomical structures can be identified through surface palpation. For example, during back surgery, superficial anatomy can be used to palpate and count vertebrae to find the site of incision. Or in phlebotomy, superficial anatomy can be used to locate an underlying vein; for example, the median cubital vein can be located by palpating the borders of the cubital fossa (such as the epicondyles of the humerus) and then looking for the superficial signs of the vein, such as size, prominence, ability to refill after depression, and feel of surrounding tissue support. As another example, in a subluxation (dislocation) of the glenohumeral joint, the bony structure becomes pronounced with the deltoid muscle failing to cover the glenohumeral joint allowing the edges of the scapula to be superficially visible. Here, the superficial anatomy is the visible edges of the scapula, implying the underlying dislocation of the joint (the related anatomical structure).
